modules.description: This module defines naming conventions for mathematical approximation schemes encompassing exponentials, logarithms, roots, trigonometric functions, and hyperbolic operations. It operates on parameterized scheme types (`'a Scheme.t`) that encapsulate table-based approximation strategies for numerical methods. These schemes are specifically designed for code generation and symbolic manipulation in floating-point arithmetic approximations, such as optimizing performance-critical numerical computations or embedded systems where precision trade-offs are required.

This module implements table-based polynomial approximations for floating-point operations, providing functions to construct and manipulate coefficient tables for numerical methods. It works with bitvectors, memory representations, and symbolic variables to approximate functions like exponentials, logarithms, and trigonometric operations. Concrete use cases include optimizing numerical computations in embedded systems or generating efficient code for symbolic manipulation where controlled precision trade-offs are acceptable.

This module implements table-based polynomial approximations for floating-point operations, offering functions to construct and manipulate coefficient tables for numerical methods. It operates on bitvectors, memory representations, and symbolic variables to approximate functions such as exponentials, logarithms, and trigonometric operations. It is used to optimize numerical computations in embedded systems and generate efficient code for symbolic manipulation with controlled precision trade-offs.
